      <entry corresp="muṟam[DEDR5005]">
        <form xml:lang="ta">muṟam</form>
        <gramGrp><gram>noun</gram></gramGrp>
        <sense><def xml:lang="en">[type of?] winnowing fan</def>
<usg xml:lang="en">
</usg>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Narrinai/NA376.xml?id=NA376&amp;w=0,2">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>muṟam</w> <w>cevi</w> <w>yāṉai<c type="geminated">t</c></w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">elephant with ears [like] winnowing fans</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Narrinai/NA376.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DNA376%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(1)"><expan ref="#NA"/> 376, line 1</ref>
</cit>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kalittokai/Kali052.xml?id=Kali52&amp;w=0,7">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>muṟam</w> <w>cevi</w> <w>maṟai<c type="geminated">p</c></w> <w>pāypu</w> <w>muraṇ</w> <w>ceyta</w> <w>puli</w> <w>ceṟṟu</w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">[the elephant] killing the tiger that has committed hostility by stealthily leaping for [its] ears</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kalittokai/Kali052.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DKali52%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(1)"><expan ref="#Kali"/> 52, line 1</ref>
</cit>
<cit>
            <ref target="https://www.ifpindia.org/digitaldb/site/digital_tevaram/U_TEV/DM1_131.HTM#p7"><expan ref="#Tev"/> 1.131.7.3f.</ref>
  <q xml:lang="ta">eḻil kuṟavar ciṟumimārkaḷ | muṟaṅkaḷiṉāl koḻittu maṇi cela</q> 
  <q xml:lang="en">as the gems come out when the graceful little girls of the hill people sift with a winnowing fan</q>
  </cit>
<note xml:lang="en">
All six early occurrences, including those from the two oldest Peruṅkāppiyam-s, form part of a miniature forumalic system that describe the ears of an elephant – the quoted Kali passage breaks up the formula and relegates the missing yāṉai  to the end of line 4. It is only the Tēvāram passage that allows a more direct understanding of what the object is used for. Of course modern dictionaries dinstinguish ciḷaku and muṟam both by form and by size, but from the available quotations one may wonder whether cuḷaku was used as a piece of kitchen equipment in food production while muṟam served other extended household purposes.
</note>
<note xml:lang="en">
Just like ciḷaku, muṟam is not glossed by any early commentator, thus making it clear that this too was regarded as an ordinary word not in need of explanation. 
</note></sense>
